# Decision-Making and Scope Control

## Core Principles
- Default to the smallest shippable slice that proves value; avoid "platform" thinking until the pilot works.
- Protect against scope creep: if a request introduces a new subsystem, write a 5-line "Why now?" and "What we cut?" note before implementing.
- Prefer integrations over rebuilds when a client already has a system of record (e.g., Phorest). Don't recreate scheduling unless it is explicitly the product.
- Any feature must answer: (1) who uses it, (2) what action they take, (3) what metric improves, (4) what can go wrong.
- When ambiguous, choose the path that reduces operational friction for the customer, even if it's less elegant.

## Do
- Ship the minimal version that validates the hypothesis.
- Question whether a feature belongs in this product or should integrate with existing tools.
- Document trade-offs when making architectural decisions.
- Prioritize customer workflow over technical elegance.

## Don't
- Build features "just in case" they're needed.
- Recreate functionality that exists in client systems.
- Add complexity without a clear user benefit.
- Assume more features = better product.

